%I A397705 #23 Jul 15 2026 19:15:58
%S A397705 7,11,23,35,83,167
%N A397705 Odd numbers m > 5, with no representation m = p + 2q with p, q prime and p <= q.
%C A397705 Confirmed complete to 10^7.
%C A397705 If we set p <= q, then the two types of Lemoine representations are 2p + q and p + 2q.
%C A397705 These are the exceptions to the large-doubled-prime form of Lemoine's conjecture: odd numbers 2N+1, which have no representation 2N+1 = p + 2q (p, q prime) and have the doubled prime as the large prime, 2q >= 2(2N+1)/3. For each representation, the doubled small prime, 2p < 2(2N+1)/3.
%C A397705 Ordinary Lemoine (which places no size condition on the doubled prime) has no exceptions; these six are exceptional only to the size-restricted form.
%C A397705 If Lemoine's conjecture holds, list is complete.
%H A397705 Emile Lemoine, <a href="https://books.google.fr/books?id=NLM5AAAAMAAJ&amp;pg=PA179cad=2#v=onepage&amp;q&amp;f=false">310. I2b</a>, L'intermédiaire des mathématiciens, 1 (1894), 179. In French.
%H A397705 Wikipedia, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lemoine%27s_conjecture">Lemoine's conjecture</a>.
%o A397705 (Python)
%o A397705 from sympy import isprime
%o A397705 def is_a(m):
%o A397705     if m % 2 == 0 or m <= 5:
%o A397705         return False
%o A397705     # no representation m = p + 2q, p,q prime, p<=q, with the doubled 2q >= 2m/3
%o A397705     return not any(isprime(q) and 2*q >= 2*m/3 and (m-2*q) >= 2 and isprime(m-2*q)
%o A397705                    for q in range((m+2)//3, (m-1)//2 + 1))
%o A397705 print([m for m in range(7, 10**7, 2) if is_a(m)])  # [7, 11, 23, 35, 83, 167]
%Y A397705 Cf. A046927, A002091, A002092, A185091, A194828, A194829, A195353, A195354.
%K A397705 nonn,more,new
%O A397705 1,1
